    <!-- <insight xml:id="insight-double-angle-theorem">
        <p>
            <strong>Core Circle Theorem: The "Double Angle" Connection</strong>
        </p>
        <p>
            The most fundamental relationship in circle geometry is the connection between the angle at the center and the angle at the edge (circumference). 
        </p>
        <p>
            Imagine anchoring two string ends on the boundary of a circle at points <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>:
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    If you pull the strings to meet exactly at the center point <m>O</m>, you form a wide, open central angle <m>\angle AOB</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    If you stretch those same strings much further back to meet at any point <m>P</m> on the opposite far edge of the circle, the angle "pinches" and becomes narrower.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
            Because the center <m>O</m> is physically closer to the arc than the far wall is, the angle at the center is always exactly <strong>twice</strong> as large as the angle at the circumference:
        </p>
        <me>\text{Angle at the Centre} = 2 \times \text{Angle at the Circumference}</me>
        <me>\angle AOB = 2 \times \angle APB</me>
        <p>
            Furthermore, as long as you stay on that same curved major segment boundary (points <m>P</m>, <m>Q</m>, and <m>R</m>), your viewing angle does not change:
        </p>
        <me>\angle APB = \angle AQB = \angle ARB</me>
    </insight> -->
<insight xml:id="insight-angles-same-arc">
    <p>
        <strong>Core Circle Theorem: Angles Subtended by the Same Arc</strong>
    </p>
    <p>
        Angles formed at the circumference by drawing lines from the same standing arc are exactly equal in measure. This is often referred to visually as the <strong>"Bow-Tie"</strong> or <strong>"Butterfly"</strong> theorem.
    </p>
    
    <p><strong>Key Takeaways and Common Misconceptions:</strong></p>
    <ul>
        <li>
            <p>
                The vertices of the angles must lie within the same circle segment. If one vertex crosses over to the opposite segment, the angles are no longer equal; they become supplementary (summing to <m>180^\circ</m>) as part of a cyclic quadrilateral.
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                Every vertex <em>must</em> touch the outer circumference boundary. The theorem fails if a vertex stops short inside the circle or extends past it.
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                In complex diagrams, the "bow-tie" shape can be rotated or obscured. Track the arms of an angle down to its endpoints on the circumference. If different angles share the exact same landing points, they are subtended by the same arc and are equal.
            </p>
        </li>
    </ul>
</insight>
    <!-- <insight>
     
    </insight> -->

    <!-- Add further instruction (not in a block) to develop ideas as needed -->

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- Add at least 3 examples -->
     <example xml:id="eg-same-arc-direct">
        <statement>
            <!-- <p><strong>Example 1</strong></p> -->
            <p>
                Points <m>A</m>, <m>B</m>, <m>C</m>, and <m>D</m> lie on the circumference of a circle in that order. Chords <m>AC</m> and <m>BD</m> intersect at point <m>X</m> inside the circle. If the angle <m>\angle ABD = 38^\circ</m>, find the measure of <m>\angle ACD</m>.
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="fig-chords-intersection-segment">
            <caption>Intersecting chords AC and BD meeting at an interior point X.</caption>
            <image width="65%">
                <latex-image>
                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.5]
                    % --- Define Coordinates on the Circle ---
                    \coordinate (O) at (0,0);
                    
                    % Points positioned in clockwise order
                    \coordinate (A) at (135:2);
                    \coordinate (B) at (45:2);
                    \coordinate (C) at (-35:2);
                    \coordinate (D) at (-115:2);

                    % --- Find Intersection Point X of Chords AC and BD ---
                    \coordinate (X) at (intersection of A--C and B--D);

                    % --- Draw Circle and Chords ---
                    \draw[thick] (O) circle (2cm);
                    \draw[thick] (A) -- (C);
                    \draw[thick] (B) -- (D);
                    
                    % Draw a dashed visual guideline showing the common shared arc base AD
                    \draw[thick, dashed, gray!60] (A) -- (B);
                    \draw[thick, dashed, gray!60] (C) -- (D);

                    % --- Annotate Angles ---
                    % Angle ABD = 38 degrees
                    \draw[shift={(B)}] (225:0.4) arc (225:192:0.4);
                    \node at (1.0,1.0) {$38^{\circ}$};

                    % Angle ACD = 38 degrees (Target Angle)
                    \draw[shift={(C)}] (145:0.4) arc (145:195:0.4);
                    \node at (1.2,-1.0) {$x^{\circ}$};

                    % --- Label Points ---
                    \fill (A) circle (1.5pt) node[above left] {$A$};
                    \fill (B) circle (1.5pt) node[above right] {$B$};
                    \fill (C) circle (1.5pt) node[below right] {$C$};
                    \fill (D) circle (1.5pt) node[below left] {$D$};
                    \fill (X) circle (1.5pt) node[below] {$X$};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
        </figure>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Identify the arc that subtends both angles:
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li><p>The angle <m>\angle ABD</m> stands on the arc <m>AD</m>.</p></li>
                <li><p>The angle <m>\angle ACD</m> also stands on the arc <m>AD</m>.</p></li>
            </ul>
            <p>
                By the Angles in the Same Segment Theorem, angles subtended by the same arc at the circumference are equal:
            </p>
            <me>\angle ACD = \angle ABD</me>
            <p>
                Since <m>\angle ABD = 38^\circ</m>, it follows directly that:
            </p>
            <me>\angle ACD = 38^\circ</me>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="eg-same-arc-algebraic-bowtie">
        <statement>
            <!-- <p><strong>Example 2</strong></p> -->
            <p>
                Four points <m>P</m>, <m>Q</m>, <m>R</m>, and <m>S</m> are positioned on a circle. Chords <m>PR</m> and <m>QS</m> cross each other. The angle subtended by arc <m>SR</m> at point <m>P</m> is <m>\angle SPR = 3x + 10^\circ</m> and at point <m>Q</m> is <m>\angle SQR = 5x - 12^\circ</m>. Solve for <m>x</m> and determine the physical size of these angles.
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="fig-chords-algebraic-same-segment">
            <caption>Intersecting chords PR and QS inside a circle.</caption>
            <image width="65%">
                <latex-image>
                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.5]
                    % --- Define Coordinates on the Circle ---
                    \coordinate (O) at (0,0);
                    \coordinate (P) at (135:2);
                    \coordinate (Q) at (45:2);
                    \coordinate (R) at (-45:2);
                    \coordinate (S) at (-135:2);

                    % --- Colored Background Shading ---
                    \fill[cyan!20] (S) -- (P) -- (R) -- cycle;
                    \fill[orange!20] (S) -- (Q) -- (R) -- cycle;

                    % --- Draw Base Circle ---
                    \draw[thick, gray] (O) circle (2cm);

                    % --- Draw Chords ---
                    \draw[thick, blue] (P) -- (R);
                    \draw[thick, blue] (P) -- (S);
                    \draw[thick, orange] (Q) -- (R);
                    \draw[thick, orange] (Q) -- (S);
                    
                    % --- Highlight Common Arc SR ---
                    \draw[line width=2pt, red] (-135:2) arc (-135:-45:2);
                    \node[red, below] at (-90:2.1) {Arc $SR$};

                    % --- Clean Angle Markers (No Clips) ---
                    % Angle SPR Marker
                    \draw[thick, blue] ($(P)+(225:0.4)$) arc (250:315:0.4);
                    \node[blue] at ($(P)+(270:0.65)$) {\small $3x + 10^{\circ}$};

                    % Angle SQR Marker
                    \draw[thick, orange] ($(Q)+(225:0.4)$) arc (250:315:0.4);
                    \node[orange] at ($(Q)+(270:0.65)$) {\small $5x - 12^{\circ}$};

                    % --- Label Points ---
                    \fill (P) circle (1.5pt) node[above left] {$P$};
                    \fill (Q) circle (1.5pt) node[above right] {$Q$};
                    \fill (R) circle (1.5pt) node[below right] {$R$};
                    \fill (S) circle (1.5pt) node[below left] {$S$};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
        </figure>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Since both angles <m>\angle SPR</m> and <m>\angle SQR</m> are subtended by the same boundary arc <m>SR</m> at the circumference, they must be equal:
            </p>
            <me>\angle SPR = \angle SQR</me>
            <p>
                Substitute the given algebraic expressions:
            </p>
            <me>3x + 10 = 5x - 12</me>
            <p>
                Isolate the variable terms:
            </p>
            <me>10 + 12 = 5x - 3x</me>
            <me>22 = 2x</me>
            <me>x = 11</me>
            <p>
                Calculate the actual size of the angles by substituting <m>x = 11</m> back into either expression:
            </p>
            <me>\angle SPR = 3(11) + 10 = 33 + 10 = 43^\circ</me>
            <me>\angle SQR = 5(11) - 12 = 55 - 12 = 43^\circ</me>
            <p>
                The value of <m>x</m> is <m>11</m>, and both angles measure <m>43^\circ</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="eg-same-arc-triangle-system">
        <statement>
            <!-- <p><strong>Example 3</strong></p> -->
            <p>
                In a circle, points <m>A</m>, <m>B</m>, <m>C</m>, and <m>D</m> are arranged such that chords <m>AC</m> and <m>BD</m> intersect at <m>E</m>. If <m>\angle BAC = 45^\circ</m> and <m>\angle AEB = 80^\circ</m>, find the measure of <m>\angle BDC</m>.
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="fig-chords-intersection-segment-angles">
            <caption>Intersecting chords AC and BD meeting at point E inside a circle.</caption>
            <image width="65%">
                <latex-image>
                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.5]
                    % --- Define Coordinates on the Circle ---
                    \coordinate (O) at (0,0);
                    \coordinate (A) at (140:2);
                    \coordinate (B) at (50:2);
                    \coordinate (C) at (-30:2);
                    \coordinate (D) at (-120:2);

                    % --- Find Intersection Point E ---
                    \coordinate (E) at (intersection of A--C and B--D);

                    % --- Colored Background Shading to Engage Learners ---
                    \fill[cyan!15] (A) -- (B) -- (E) -- cycle;

                    % --- Draw Base Circle ---
                    \draw[thick, gray] (O) circle (2cm);

                    % --- Draw Chords and Inner Lines ---
                    \draw[thick, blue] (A) -- (C);
                    \draw[thick, blue] (B) -- (D);
                    \draw[thick, orange] (A) -- (B);
                    \draw[thick, orange] (C) -- (D);
                    
                    % --- Highlight Common Shared Arc BC ---
                    \draw[line width=2.5pt, red] (50:2) arc (50:-30:2);
                    \node[red, right] at (10:2.1) {Arc $BC$};

                    % --- Clean Interior Angle Markers ---
                    % Angle BAC at vertex A
                    \draw[thick, blue] (A) ++(-40:0.4) arc (-40:-77:0.4);
                    \node[blue, below right] at ($(A)+( -55:0.55)$) {\small $45^{\circ}$};

                    % Angle AEB at vertex E
                    \draw[thick, gray!80!black] (E) ++(50:0.3) arc (50:140:0.3);
                    \node[gray!80!black, above] at ($(E)+(90:0.35)$) {\small $80^{\circ}$};

                    % Target Angle BDC at vertex D
                    \draw[thick, orange] (D) ++(60:0.4) arc (60:97:0.4);
                    \node[orange, above left] at ($(D)+(78:0.55)$) {\small ?};

                    % --- Label Points ---
                    \fill (A) circle (1.5pt) node[above left] {$A$};
                    \fill (B) circle (1.5pt) node[above right] {$B$};
                    \fill (C) circle (1.5pt) node[below right] {$C$};
                    \fill (D) circle (1.5pt) node[below left] {$D$};
                    \fill (E) circle (1.5pt) node[below] {$E$};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
        </figure>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Let us analyze triangle <m>ABE</m> first to find the angle <m>\angle ABD</m> (which is the same as <m>\angle ABE</m>):
            </p>
            <p>
                The sum of angles in triangle <m>ABE</m> is <m>180^\circ</m>:
            </p>
            <me>\angle BAE + \angle AEB + \angle ABE = 180^\circ</me>
            <me>45^\circ + 80^\circ + \angle ABE = 180^\circ</me>
            <me>125^\circ + \angle ABE = 180^\circ</me>
            <me>\angle ABE = 55^\circ \implies \angle ABD = 55^\circ</me>
            <p>
                Now, identify the relationship between <m>\angle ABD</m> and the target angle <m>\angle BDC</m> (which is the same as <m>\angle ADC</m>):
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li><p>The angle <m>\angle ABD</m> is subtended by arc <m>AD</m> at the circumference.</p></li>
                <li><p>The angle <m>\angle ACD</m> is also subtended by arc <m>AD</m>.</p></li>
            </ul>
            <p>
                However, looking closely at the diagram, the target angle is <m>\angle BDC</m>. Let's identify its subtending arc:
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li><p><m>\angle BDC</m> stands on the arc <m>BC</m>.</p></li>
                <li><p>The angle <m>\angle BAC</m> also stands on the arc <m>BC</m>.</p></li>
            </ul>
            <p>
                Applying the Angles in the Same Segment Theorem:
            </p>
            <me>\angle BDC = \angle BAC</me>
            <p>
                Since <m>\angle BAC = 45^\circ</m>, it follows directly that:
            </p>
            <me>\angle BDC = 45^\circ</me>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example xml:id="eg-same-arc-system-algebra">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Two distinct angles on a circumference, <m>\angle PQS</m> and <m>\angle PRS</m>, stand on the same arc <m>PS</m>. If <m>\angle PQS = 3a + 2b</m> and <m>\angle PRS = a + 4b</m> where the physical measure of <m>\angle PQS = 54^\circ</m>, find the values of constants <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>.
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-angles-same-segment-algebraic">
            <caption>Two distinct inscribed angles sharing the common base arc PS.</caption>
            <image width="65%">
                <latex-image>
                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.5]
                    % --- Define Coordinates on the Circle ---
                    \coordinate (O) at (0,0);
                    \coordinate (P) at (-135:2);
                    \coordinate (S) at (-45:2);
                    \coordinate (Q) at (135:2);
                    \coordinate (R) at (45:2);

                    % --- Colored Background Shading for Visual Engagement ---
                    \fill[cyan!15] (P) -- (Q) -- (S) -- cycle;
                    \fill[orange!15] (P) -- (R) -- (S) -- cycle;

                    % --- Draw Base Circle ---
                    \draw[thick, gray] (O) circle (2cm);

                    % --- Draw Chords ---
                    \draw[thick, blue] (Q) -- (P);
                    \draw[thick, blue] (Q) -- (S);
                    \draw[thick, orange] (R) -- (P);
                    \draw[thick, orange] (R) -- (S);
                    
                    % --- Highlight Common Shared Arc PS ---
                    \draw[line width=2.5pt, red] (-135:2) arc (-135:-45:2);
                    \node[red, below] at (-90:2.1) {Arc $PS$};

                    % --- Clean Interior Angle Markers ---
                    % Angle PQS Marker (Vertex Q)
                    \draw[thick, blue] (Q) ++(287:0.4) arc (287:323:0.4);
                    \node[blue] at ($(Q)+(270:0.65)$) {\small $3a + 2b$};

                    % Angle PRS Marker (Vertex R)
                    \draw[thick, orange] (R) ++(217:0.4) arc (217:253:0.4);
                    \node[orange] at ($(R)+(270:0.65)$) {\small $a + 4b$};

                    % --- Label Points ---
                    \fill (P) circle (1.5pt) node[below left] {$P$};
                    \fill (S) circle (1.5pt) node[below right] {$S$};
                    \fill (Q) circle (1.5pt) node[above left] {$Q$};
                    \fill (R) circle (1.5pt) node[above right] {$R$};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
        </figure>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Since both angles stand on the same arc <m>PS</m> at the circumference, they must be equal to each other:
                </p>
                <me>\angle PQS = \angle PRS</me>
                <p>
                    We are given that <m>\angle PQS = 54^\circ</m>, which means both algebraic expressions are equal to <m>54</m>:
                </p>
                <me>3a + 2b = 54 \quad \text{--- (Equation 1)}</me>
                <me>a + 4b = 54 \quad \text{--- (Equation 2)}</me>
                <p>
                    We can solve this system of linear equations. Multiply Equation 1 by <m>2</m> to match the <m>b</m> terms:
                </p>
                <me>6a + 4b = 108 \quad \text{--- (Equation 3)}</me>
                <p>
                    Subtract Equation 2 from Equation 3:
                </p>
                <me>(6a + 4b) - (a + 4b) = 108 - 54</me>
                <me>5a = 54</me>
                <me>a = 10.8</me>
                <p>
                    Substitute <m>a = 10.8</m> back into Equation 2 to find <m>b</m>:
                </p>
                <me>10.8 + 4b = 54</me>
                <me>4b = 54 - 10.8</me>
                <me>4b = 43.2</me>
                <me>b = 10.8</me>
                <p>
                    The constants are <m>a = 10.8</m> and <m>b = 10.8</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>

