    <!-- Add static exercises -->
     <exercises xml:id="ex-same-arc-only-practice">

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    On a circular radar display, two sensor beams originate from the same boundary points <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>. One beam meets the outer ring at target point <m>P</m> and the other meets at target point <m>Q</m>. If the angle measured at target <m>P</m> is <m>\angle APB = 44^\circ</m>, calculate the angle <m>\angle AQB</m> measured at target <m>Q</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Both angles <m>\angle APB</m> and <m>\angle AQB</m> are subtended at the circumference by the exact same boundary arc <m>AB</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    According to the theorem, angles standing on the same arc are equal in measure:
                </p>
                <me>\angle AQB = \angle APB = 44^\circ</me>
                <p>
                    The measure of the angle <m>\angle AQB</m> is <m>44^\circ</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Four points <m>W</m>, <m>X</m>, <m>Y</m>, and <m>Z</m> are spaced sequentially on a circle. Chords <m>WY</m> and <m>XZ</m> cross at an intersection point <m>E</m>. If <m>\angle XWZ = 27^\circ</m>, identify which other angle in the circle must be exactly <m>27^\circ</m> and write down your geometric reasoning.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Trace the arms of the angle <m>\angle XWZ</m> back to their endpoints on the circumference. The angle stands on the arc <m>XZ</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Now locate the other angle that has its vertex on the circumference and stands on the same arc <m>XZ</m>. This is angle <m>\angle XYZ</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    By the theorem that angles standing on the same arc are equal:
                </p>
                <me>\angle XYZ = \angle XWZ = 27^\circ</me>
                <p>
                    The angle <m>\angle XYZ</m> (or <m>\angle XYE</m>) is <m>27^\circ</m> because both stand on arc <m>XZ</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Two angles on the circumference of a circle stand on the same arc <m>MN</m>. The first angle is <m>\angle MKN = 3k + 12^\circ</m> and the second is <m>\angle MLN = 5k - 8^\circ</m>. Solve for <m>k</m> and determine the actual measure of the angles.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Since both angles stand on the same arc <m>MN</m> at the circumference, they must be equal:
                </p>
                <me>\angle MKN = \angle MLN</me>
                <me>3k + 12 = 5k - 8</me>
                <p>
                    Isolate the terms with variable <m>k</m>:
                </p>
                <me>12 + 8 = 5k - 3k</me>
                <me>20 = 2k</me>
                <me>k = 10</me>
                <p>
                    Substitute <m>k = 10</m> back into either equation to calculate the angle measure:
                </p>
                <me>\angle MKN = 3(10) + 12 = 30 + 12 = 42^\circ</me>
                <p>
                    The value of <m>k</m> is <m>10</m>, and both angles measure <m>42^\circ</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    In a circle, chords <m>PR</m> and <m>QS</m> cross at point <m>T</m> inside the circle. If the angle <m>\angle SPQ = 68^\circ</m> and the vertical angle of the intersection is <m>\angle PTQ = 82^\circ</m>, find the measure of <m>\angle PRQ</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Let us first analyze triangle <m>PTQ</m>. The angle <m>\angle PTQ = 82^\circ</m> and <m>\angle SPQ = 68^\circ</m> (which is the same as <m>\angle TPQ = 68^\circ</m>).
                </p>
                <p>
                    Calculate the third angle <m>\angle TQP</m> in triangle <m>PTQ</m>:
                </p>
                <me>\angle TQP = 180^\circ - (82^\circ + 68^\circ)</me>
                <me>\angle TQP = 180^\circ - 150^\circ = 30^\circ</me>
                <p>
                    Note that the angle <m>\angle TQP</m> is the same as <m>\angle SQP</m>. This angle stands on the boundary arc <m>SP</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Identify the standing arc for the target angle <m>\angle PRQ</m> (which is <m>\angle SRQ</m>):
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li><p><m>\angle PRQ</m> stands on the arc <m>PQ</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p>The angle <m>\angle PSQ</m> also stands on the arc <m>PQ</m>.</p></li>
                </ul>
                <p>
                    Let's find the measure of <m>\angle PSQ</m> (which is <m>\angle PST</m>). In triangle <m>PTS</m>, the vertical angle <m>\angle PTS = \angle PTQ = 82^\circ</m> (vertically opposite). 
                </p>
                <p>
                    However, we can look at the standing arcs directly:
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li><p><m>\angle PRQ</m> stands on arc <m>PQ</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p><m>\angle PSQ</m> stands on arc <m>PQ</m>.</p></li>
                </ul>
                <p>
                    Also:
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li><p><m>\angle SPQ = 68^\circ</m> stands on arc <m>SQ</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p><m>\angle SRQ</m> must also stand on arc <m>SQ</m>, which means <m>\angle SRQ = 68^\circ</m>.</p></li>
                </ul>
                <p>
                    Now let's trace the angle <m>\angle SQP = 30^\circ</m>, which stands on arc <m>SP</m>. The angle <m>\angle SRP</m> (which is <m>\angle PRQ</m>) also stands on arc <m>SP</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Therefore, by the theorem:
                </p>
                <me>\angle PRQ = \angle SQP = 30^\circ</me>
                <p>
                    The measure of the angle <m>\angle PRQ</m> is <m>30^\circ</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    An arc <m>AB</m> subtends two angles at the circumference of a circle, <m>\angle APB = x^2 - 10^\circ</m> and <m>\angle AQB = 3x + 18^\circ</m>. Set up a quadratic equation, solve for the positive value of <m>x</m>, and calculate the size of <m>\angle APB</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Since both angles stand on the same arc <m>AB</m> at the circumference, they are equal:
                </p>
                <me>x^2 - 10 = 3x + 18</me>
                <p>
                    Rearrange the terms to form a standard quadratic equation (<m>ax^2 + bx + c = 0</m>):
                </p>
                <me>x^2 - 3x - 10 - 18 = 0</me>
                <me>x^2 - 3x - 28 = 0</me>
                <p>
                    Factor the quadratic expression (find two numbers that multiply to <m>-28</m> and add to <m>-3</m>, which are <m>-7</m> and <m>4</m>):
                </p>
                <me>(x - 7)(x + 4) = 0</me>
                <p>
                    This gives two possible solutions:
                </p>
                <me>x = 7 \quad \text{or} \quad x = -4</me>
                <p>
                    Since we are looking for the positive value of <m>x</m>, we select <m>x = 7</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Calculate the actual angle size:
                </p>
                <me>\angle APB = (7)^2 - 10 = 49 - 10 = 39^\circ</me>
                <p>
                    The positive value of <m>x</m> is <m>7</m>, and the angle size is <m>39^\circ</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>

